   537	## §5. Failure-mode handling
   538	
   539	### §5.1 If a gate doesn't pass
   540	
   541	**Per-gate failure pattern:**
   542	1. Identify which gate criterion failed (specific, evidence-grounded).
   543	2. Identify which phase produced the failing artifact.
   544	3. Loop back to that phase OR earlier phase if the failure traces upstream.
   545	4. Record the loop-back trigger explicitly (in audit DISPOSITION.md and in coordination layer).
   546	5. Re-execute affected phases.
   547	6. Re-fire gate.
   548	
   549	**Do not bypass gates with Logan-discretion** (except where explicit Logan-discretion is named in the gate-criteria — e.g., Phase F criterion 5 "no outstanding load-bearing-decisions block extraction" is Logan-disposed; criterion 3 internal-coherence is audit-disposed).
   550	
   551	### §5.2 If new framing-bleed surfaces mid-execution
   552	
   553	**Pattern:** A later-phase audit catches framing-bleed that earlier-phase audits missed. Treat as a revealed-residual, not as audit-failure.
   554	
   555	1. Apply premise-bleed audit-arc pattern (similar to what we just did): cross-vendor + same-vendor-independent + differential + Logan-disposition.
   556	2. Fix at point-of-bleed (likely an earlier phase artifact).
   557	3. Re-run downstream phases as needed.
   558	4. Update §0.6 failure-mode taxonomy if a new kind of erring is discovered.
