     1	# AGENTS.md
     2	
     3	This file defines how agents should work in this repository during the bootstrap phase.
     4	
     5	## Mission
     6	
     7	Help build an MCP-native research discovery substrate inspired by arxiv-sanity, while preserving the most important product values:
     8	
     9	- discovery over overload,
    10	- explicit and steerable taste / interest modeling,
    11	- fast browse / triage loops,
    12	- recent-paper monitoring,
    13	- and inspectable ranking and provenance.
    14	
    15	## Do not do these things
    16	
    17	Do **not**:
    18	
    19	- assume tags are the final or canonical taste representation,
    20	- assume dense retrieval is obviously the winner,
    21	- assume lexical retrieval is obsolete,
    22	- assume the first MCP interface should mirror a web UI,
    23	- assume “paper chat” is the product,
    24	- serve or redistribute full text without checking license / provenance implications,
    25	- collapse open questions into hidden code assumptions.
    26	
    27	## Default working posture
    28	
    29	Unless an ADR says otherwise:
    30	
    31	1. keep the design space open,
    32	2. prefer cheap defaults,
    33	3. preserve reversibility,
    34	4. record uncertainty explicitly,
    35	5. separate hypotheses from decisions.
    36	
    37	## Project-specific anti-patterns to detect
    38	
    39	Patterns this project has already drifted into once (the 005-008 spike chain is the canonical case). When you notice one, name it; surface it to a deliberation rather than working around it. Cite-back to `LONG-ARC.md` per pattern so duplication-drift between this section and the source is detectable on next-pass review.
    40	
    41	- **Tournament narrowing under "disciplined" framing** (`LONG-ARC.md:47`). Sequentially pruning a candidate set toward a winner. Counter-posture: rank-and-deprioritize, not eliminate; multi-lens framing replaces winner-pick.
    42	- **Single-lens "interface" by accident** (`LONG-ARC.md:48`). Shipping a lens abstraction alongside only one lens — the abstraction ends up shaped exactly to that lens. Counter-posture: validate abstractions by shipping a second implementation, per ADR-0005.
    43	- **Silent defaults** (`LONG-ARC.md:49`). A reference frame becomes the implicit baseline that all alternatives are measured against, even when nothing argued for it being baseline. Counter-posture: name the reference frame explicitly; require challengers measured against multiple frames or task outcomes.
    44	- **ADR violation by gradual local-reasonable steps** (`LONG-ARC.md:50`). Each step locally defensible; cumulative drift away from an accepted ADR. Counter-posture: run an ADR-against-current-work check at deliberation boundaries (see below); ADRs are read at planning time, not just at writing time.
    45	- **Closure pressure at every layer** (`LONG-ARC.md:51`). Confident remedies, prescriptive language, calibrated language reserved for closing footnotes. Counter-posture: calibrated language as default register; flag confident-sounding remedies for paired review before adoption (see `METHODOLOGY.md:104-115`, M1).
    46	- **Embedding-model choice as load-bearing decision** (`LONG-ARC.md:52`). Treating "which model wins" as the architectural commitment when most leverage lives upstream. Counter-posture: treat embedding-model selection as one lens-design decision among many.
    47	- **Single-reader framing claims as authoritative** (`LONG-ARC.md:53`). Audit memos and framing critiques produced by one reader propagated as ground truth. Counter-posture: paired review for framing claims (cross-vendor + same-vendor); consult `METHODOLOGY.md` (M1 status: Hypothesis as of 2026-04-26 update at line 119).
    48	
    49	## Required habits for agents
    50	
    51	### 1. Mark your level of commitment
    52	When proposing architecture or API changes, explicitly classify them as:
    53	
    54	- Settled
    55	- Chosen for now
    56	- Hypothesis
    57	- Open
    58	
    59	### 2. Update the right document
    60	- New durable decision -> add or update an ADR
    61	- New experiment -> update `docs/08-evaluation-and-experiments.md` and/or use the experiment template
    62	- New unresolved issue -> update `docs/10-open-questions.md`
    63	- New external precedent or pattern -> update `docs/04-reference-designs.md`
    64	
    65	### 3. Respect the core constraints
    66	Always keep in mind:
    67	
    68	- **Time semantics matter**: submission, update, and announcement are not the same thing.
    69	- **License semantics matter**: metadata, full text, PDFs, source, and derived content have different reuse constraints.
    70	- **Provenance matters**: store where every ranking signal, content artifact, or taste signal came from.
    71	- **Cost matters**: do not require expensive embeddings or heavyweight infrastructure without a strong reason.
    72	- **Explainability matters**: prefer systems that can explain why a paper was returned.
    73	
    74	### 4. Prefer these abstractions
    75	Use these terms unless there is a better reason not to:
    76	
    77	- **paper**
    78	- **content variant**
    79	- **interest profile**
    80	- **collection**
    81	- **saved query**
    82	- **watch**
    83	- **triage state**
    84	- **result set**
    85	- **ranking explanation**
    86	
    87	Avoid hardcoding the system around `tag -> papers` as the universal model.
    88	
    89	## Default implementation bias
    90	
    91	The default bias for early implementation should be:
    92	
    93	- metadata mirror before heavy content mirroring,
    94	- lexical baseline before semantic-only retrieval,
    95	- candidate generation + reranking architecture,
    96	- lazy enrichment over eager enrichment,
    97	- small MCP surface with strong primitives,
    98	- explicit workflow state for agents,
    99	- local-first where feasible.
   100	
   101	## Before you make a major change
   102	
   103	Ask:
   104	
   105	1. Does this preserve the soul of arxiv-sanity?
   106	2. Does this reduce or increase irreversible commitment?
   107	3. Can we evaluate it against a baseline?
   108	4. What is the cost impact?
   109	5. What is the legal / licensing impact?
   110	6. What new provenance do we need to track?
   111	
   112	## Definition of success for early agents
   113	
   114	A successful early contribution is one that makes the project:
   115	
   116	- more testable,
   117	- more explainable,
   118	- more modular,
   119	- more license-aware,
   120	- and more capable of comparing alternatives without repeated rewrites.
   121	
   122	## CONTEXT.md epistemic discipline
   123	
   124	When creating or updating CONTEXT.md files and other planning artifacts:
   125	
   126	### Separate traceable claims from derived and interpretive ones
   127	- **Source-traceable**: Claim directly restates a specific passage in user-authored docs (01-11), an accepted ADR, or an explicit user instruction. Cite the source.
   128	- **Artifact-reported**: Claim directly reports what an inspected code path, experiment artifact, log, or checked-in output says. Keep scope narrow and name the artifact.
   129	- **Derived**: Claim combines traceable items with a small, explicit inferential step. Mark it as `[derived]` and state the bridge.
   130	- **Interpretive**: Claim depends on substantive framing, analogy, or explanatory judgment. Mark it as `[interpretive]` or `[chosen for now]` with reasoning.
   131	- **Never** present a derived or interpretive claim as if it were source-traceable or artifact-reported.
   132	- Avoid bare `grounded` as an epistemic label in new planning artifacts. It is too overloaded and too easily heard as "validated" or "settled."
   133	- Older artifacts may still use the legacy `grounded / inferred` language. Treat it as historical terminology, not the preferred schema for new work.
   134	
   135	### Do not close Open Questions without authority
   136	- Items in `docs/10-open-questions.md` are **intentionally unresolved** by the user.
   137	- An AI agent may **propose** an answer (mark as `[chosen for now]`) but must not silently adopt it as settled.
   138	- Closing an Open Question requires: user confirmation, or a new ADR with explicit rationale.
   139	- If implementation requires choosing an answer, document it as provisional and flag for user review.
   140	
   141	### ADR citations must be specific
   142	- When citing an ADR to justify a decision, quote the specific clause or principle that applies.
   143	- Do not cite an ADR number alone as blanket authority for decisions the ADR does not address.
   144	- Example (verbatim quote, with deliberate fidelity to ADR text): ADR-0001 states "multiple retrieval and ranking strategies can coexist" (`docs/adrs/ADR-0001-exploration-first.md:22`) — this is a capability commitment about the architecture (the design must support coexistence), not a directive that every project decision *must* engage multiple strategies. Compare to the inflated paraphrase "multiple retrieval/ranking strategies must coexist" — that paraphrase converts a permission into a directive and is therefore inaccurate, even though it sounds more authoritative. Earlier versions of this section misquoted ADR-0001 as "must coexist"; corrected per the discipline being taught.
   145	
   146	### No speculative product strategy
   147	- CONTEXT.md files describe implementation decisions, not business models or monetization.
   148	- Product strategy (pricing, donation models, growth) is out of scope unless the user introduces it.
   149	
   150	## Deliberation boundaries
   151	
   152	Some change-types deserve a pause-and-surface step before proceeding — propose the change, name the alternatives, and wait for confirmation rather than auto-executing. The list below is conditional ("when X, do Y"), not absolute. When in doubt about whether a change qualifies, surface it; the cost of pausing is small.
   153	
   154	When proposing a change that fits any of the items below, state: (i) the observed problem; (ii) the proposed change; (iii) why now; (iv) alternatives considered; (v) the expected write-set; (vi) verification plan.
   155	
   156	- **When reshaping a spike, milestone, or phase plan structurally** (not minor edits) — surface and propose; do not restructure in place.
   157	- **When modifying any accepted ADR's text, status, or scope** — surface and propose; ADRs are read at planning time and accepted via deliberation, not amended silently.
   158	- **When introducing or removing a top-level abstraction** (lens type, signal type, workflow primitive) — surface and propose; check the abstraction against ADR-0005's "validate by shipping a second implementation" discipline.
   159	- **When changing the MCP tool / resource / prompt surface in ways visible to existing callers** — surface and propose; backward-compat semantics are part of the surface contract.
   160	- **When editing `LONG-ARC.md`, `VISION.md`, or the project root `CLAUDE.md` / `AGENTS.md`** — surface and propose; doctrine-layer changes warrant deliberation rather than in-place editing during routine work.
   161	- **When closing an Open Question** (per `docs/10-open-questions.md`) without a new ADR or explicit user confirmation — do not close; mark `[chosen for now]` instead and flag for review.
   162	
   163	Once v0.2 introduces the `Lens` interface, `signal_type` registry, and MCP-tool lens-awareness surfaces, those should be tracked as protected-seams subject to the change-control discipline above; the specific tracking mechanism (a list inline here, a dedicated artifact, or a harness-level mechanism) is to be decided when the surfaces ship. The list does not yet exist because the surfaces do not yet exist.

