   512	The two-step conditional vendor disposition (rule 1) sits between the reviewer's two-step (always run both same-vendor + cross-vendor) and Claude's earlier three-step extension (always run cross-vendor + same-vendor + differential). Cross-vendor baseline is the structural floor — the cross-vendor reader is the one who can detect shared Claude+Logan framing. Same-vendor stress adds value only when cross-vendor surfaces Class C candidates Claude reading might re-classify or supplement. Below Class C, same-vendor stress likely catches register-shaped items below load-bearing-ness threshold and is not worth the dispatch. Conditional escalation matches B2's existing per-slice-W2-audit-disposition discipline.
   513	
   514	The negative-space check (rule 2) is the review's most important methodological catch (per deliberation log §4.1). Vocabulary-only lens catches what was *said*, not what was *omitted*. Premise-bleed via omission is exactly the failure mode Logan's premise-correction concern flagged. The original spec's lens-questions named the right targets (under-weighting; question-shape) but the method didn't operationalize how to find them. The negative-space check fixes this directly and couples to grounding (rule 5) for the reference frame.
   515	
   516	The vetted-replacement vocabulary (rule 3) goes beyond the reviewer's "be more careful" recommendation because for an audit specifically about vocabulary precision, "be more careful" without explicit replacements reintroduces the original problem (the auditor constructs its own replacements; inherits compression-shape). Vetted-replacement-with-citations transfers the precision-burden from auditor judgment to spec authorship.
   517	
   518	The scope hybrid (rules 4 + 5) resolves the original spec's internal contradiction: motivation invoked propagation but scope excluded slice outputs, and grounding was forbidden but corrected-frame claims rest on source-grounded knowledge. Targeted-sampling under hard cap + prior-audit-first grounding with narrow-source-reading fallback are bounded inclusions that fix the contradiction without expanding into substance-audit territory.
   519	
   520	The output rename (rule 6) and read budget (rule 7) are localized cleanups: the original "Recommendation shape" conflated auditor-signal with Logan-disposition; the original cost estimate was sloppy. Rename + per-option justification preserves auditor's helpful signal while honoring Logan-disposes-only discipline; explicit read budget with conditional add-ons makes the scope-expansion paths honest.
   521	
   522	**Determining assumptions.**
   523	
   524	1. v1-GSD-bleed concern is plausibly load-bearing for §2.1 (R4 disposition-timing — exactly where runtime-application weighting matters) and §5.2 (R-mix decomposition shape — depends on which surfaces are first-class), per SYNTHESIS-COMPARISON.md §4.4 + Logan's premise-correction message.
   525	2. M1 register-vs-substance asymmetry is empirically more complex than original claim (per SYNTHESIS-COMPARISON.md §4.1); cross-vendor catches what same-vendor cannot detect when same-vendor shares the artifact's framing. Vendor selection rule rests on this.
   526	3. Prior cross-vendor-codebase-understanding-audit is substantially robust against v1-GSD-bleed (because it was cross-vendor) but not necessarily fully robust at the runtime-application-surface-weighting level. Hybrid grounding (prior-audit primary + narrow source-reading fallback) hedges against this residual risk.
   527	4. Cost of mis-calibrated §2.1 / §5 incubation disposition under bled-frame is materially higher than cost of running the audit. 1-3 hour audit-time + ~45-90 min spec-revision-time is justified.
   528	5. Auditor calibration on bounded sampling (rule 4 hard cap; rule 5 max 5 source reads) holds in practice. Without this assumption, scope creep into substance-audit territory becomes a real risk.
   529	
   530	**What would change the decision.**
   531	
   532	- *If Logan reads bleed concern as cosmetic Class-A-only*: simplify rule 1 to cross-vendor-only single-step (no conditional escalation); drop rule 2 negative-space check to optional; drop rule 5 source-reading fallback; spec revision becomes lighter (~15-25% rewrite).
   533	- *If Logan reads bleed as definitively load-bearing*: force three-step (Claude's earlier extension; same-vendor stress always runs) per rule 1; no other changes.
   534	- *If Logan distrusts conditional dispositions in general* (per §1.12 "If you'd rather not maintain per-slice audit-disposition decisions"): pre-commit to two-step always per reviewer's recommendation; drop conditional escalation.
   535	- *If Logan distrusts the "small substance-territory door" of source-reading fallback* (rule 5): drop source-reading; prior-audit grounding only.
   536	- *If Logan reads vetted-replacement extension as over-engineering* (rule 3): drop the extension; "be more careful" instruction in spec; risk additional auditor inheritance.
   537	- *If Logan reads cross-vendor codex baseline as too independent* (i.e., codex doesn't natively know v1-GSD; lens-construction in spec is necessary): swap rule 1's Step-1 to same-vendor adversarial-auditor with explicit shared-frame caveat acknowledged in spec; less-clean structurally but better lens-comprehension.
   538	- *If prior-audit's META-SYNTHESIS is found unreliable* on inspection (rule 5 grounding): swap rule 5 to source-reading-primary instead of fallback; heavier audit-time but cleaner independence.
   539	
   540	**Confidence.** Medium-high. Each rule rests on specific evidence (SYNTHESIS-COMPARISON.md §4.1 inversion observation; reviewer's findings; deliberation log §3 analysis). Rules 1 + 2 + 5 form a coherent triad addressing "what stable independent reference frame can the auditor anchor to" (per deliberation log §4.2). Rules 4 + 6 + 7 are localized refinements. Rule 3 (vetted-replacement) is the rule most likely to be revised post-spec-revision if Logan reads the extension as over-engineering. Adjudication-uncertainty notes per finding live in deliberation log §6.
   541	
   542	**Log reference.** `.planning/deliberations/2026-04-28-audit-spec-review-deliberation.md` (full deliberation; §3 Claude analysis; §4 cross-cutting observations; §5 per-finding adjudications with rationale + where-Logan-might-differ + revision-implication; §6 revision-action table). Predecessor methodological observation: `.planning/gsd-2-uplift/exploration/SYNTHESIS-COMPARISON.md` §4.1 (M1 mixed observation) + §4.4 (framing-import drift signal that motivated the audit). Predecessor decisions: §1.12 (B2 selective-audit discipline that conditional-escalation mirrors); §1.13 (B3 vendor-scope that this rule extends).
